  "prompt": "What's a good product for Acne?",
  "response": "Treating acne often requires a tailored approach based on the severity and type of acne. However, some commonly recommended over-the-counter and prescription products are:\n\n1. **Benzoyl Peroxide** - Available in various strengths, benzoyl peroxide helps to kill acne-causing bacteria, reduce inflammation, and clear pores. Brands like Clearasil and PanOxyl offer benzoyl peroxide products.\n\n2. **Salicylic Acid** - Found in numerous forms such as cleansers, toners, and spot treatments, salicylic acid works by exfoliating the skin and keeping pores clear. Products like Neutrogena Oil-Free Acne Wash contain salicylic acid.\n\n3. **Retinoids** - These vitamin A derivatives can help unclog pores and reduce inflammation. Adapalene gel, a type of retinoid, is available over-the-counter under the brand name Differin.\n\n4. **Alpha Hydroxy Acids (AHAs)** - AHAs like glycolic acid and lactic acid exfoliate the skin, which can help improve acne and overall skin texture. Pixi Glow Tonic is a popular product containing glycolic acid.\n\n5. **Sulfur** - Sulfur helps to dry out the surface of the skin to absorb excess oil and reduce inflammation. It's found in products like Proactiv Skin Smoothing Exfoliator.\n\n6. **Tea Tree Oil** - Known for its antimicrobial properties, tea tree oil can be an effective natural alternative. The Body Shop offers a tea tree oil line that targets acne.\n\n7. **Niacinamide** - This is a form of Vitamin B3 that helps reduce inflammation and oil production. The Ordinary's Niacinamide 10% + Zinc 1% is a popular choice.\n\n8. **Azelaic Acid** - Found in products like The Ordinary Azelaic Acid Suspension, it helps to clear pores and reduce inflammation.\n\nFor persistent or severe acne, consulting a dermatologist is important as they can prescribe stronger treatments such as oral antibiotics, hormonal treatments, or stronger topical medications.\n\nWhen starting any new product, it's advisable to test it on a small area of skin first and introduce one product at a time to monitor how your skin reacts. Additionally, maintaining a consistent skincare routine and being patient will help in managing acne effectively.",
